Hedonic Home Price Prediction in Miami, Florida

1.1 Introduction

In order to better factor in local intelligence, our team was tasked with building a better predictive model of home prices for Miami, Florida (Miami Beach was also included, but for brevity the combined municipalities will be referred to as Miami). Using data gathered from online open data resources and OLS regression, we created a model that predicted sale prices. We attempted to minimize average error and create a model that is both accurate and generalizable across space. While we initially collected many variables, we found that a simple model including only four features was best able to predict sale prices. This is because our models with many features included colinear features, and thus, were overfitted. By including neighborhood and the average sale price of surrounding homes, we were able to better predict sale prices across neighborhoods and, importantly, within neighborhoods. The following map depicts the the distribution of sale prices of the provided homes across Miami.

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2)
  )
}

}

# Load Quantile break functions

qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]]), digits = 3),
                 c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T)
  }
}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

# Load nn function

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) { 
  measureFrom_Matrix <- as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <- as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()}

  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop, 0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop), 0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),

1.2 Data

Features

While our final model only includes the features of neighborhood, zoning class, average sale price of the five nearest homes, and dock, we began by collecting as many features as we could find. We found data for our features from online open data sources, including the Miami-Dade County Open Data Hub. We also engineered features from within the housing data we were given. Our original features included everything from distance to the beach to school district. After thorough analysis, we narrowed our features down to the final four included the in the model. Our features are split between internal characteristics, amenities/public services, and spatial structures.

Correlations

We created a correlation matrix to examine the correlations between our features. If two features are strongly correlated with each other, it means that they are colinear. Collinearity creates a bad model, because if both correlated features are put into the regression, one will be insignificant. We found that while lagLot and lagSQ were the only two features strongly correlated with each other (r > .8), many other features were moderately correlated. We carefully examined these correlations, as well as each features correlation with Sale Price to decide which features to use in our model.

1.2 Methods

We created the desired sale price prediction model using the following steps. First, we examined the correlation between each feature and sale price, looking for those features with the strongest relationships. We also examined the correlations between each feature to look for collinearity. Using this information, we narrowed down our features to exclude features that were strongly correlated to each other and those with a weak correlation to sale price. We then found the R^2 and MAE for the model which includes all of our variables as a baseline. R^2 is the proportion of variance in sale price which can be explained by our features. While R^2 shows how well our model fits the data we have, a high R^2 value doesnt mean the model is good at predicting prices of unseen data. MAE or mean absolute error is a better measure of how good a model is good at prediction. The MAE is found by splitting the house points we have into a training and test set. Using the model created with the training set we predicted sale prices for the test set. These are then compared to the actual known sale prices of the test set to determine the error. The MAE is average of the absolute error for each of the predicted sale prices. We created a function which determined every single combination of features which could go into a model. We then had a function test every combination to determine which combinations of features produced the lowest MAE. We then used cross-validation to test the models across different random samples of data. We also examined if our model was good at predicting across neighborhoods and within neighborhoods and checked to see if our larger absolute errors were clustered.
